events.description: Weekly report by the Mortgage Bankers Association for the week ended January 30, detailing mortgage rates and application volumes.
A significant winter storm that impacted much of the United States, affecting economic activity and homebuying.

facts.fact_text: The average contract rate on 30-year fixed-rate mortgages fell to 6.21% for the week ended January 30.

evidences.evidence_text: The average contract rate on 30-year fixed-rate mortgages for conforming loans of $806,500 or less in the US fell to 6.21% in the week ended January 30

facts.fact_text: Mortgage applications declined by 8.9% in the week ended January 30.

evidences.evidence_text: mortgage applications declined 8.9%, extending an 8.5% drop in the previous week

facts.fact_text: Refinancing applications decreased by 4.7% and the purchase index fell by 14.4%.

evidences.evidence_text: Refinancing applications went down 4.7%, after a 15.7% drop and the purchase index tumbled 14.4% after decreasing 0.4%.

claims.claim_text: Winter Storm Fern likely hampered homebuying activity because much of the country was snowed in.
claims.author: Joel Kan

evidences.evidence_text: Winter Storm Fern likely had an impact as much of the country was snowed in, hampering homebuying activity.

claims.claim_text: The annual increase in purchase applications reached its weakest point since April 2025.
claims.author: Joel Kan

evidences.evidence_text: The annual increase in purchase applications was the weakest since April 2025

evidence.evidence_text: Winter Storm Fern likely had an impact as much of the country was snowed in, hampering homebuying activity.
The average contract rate on 30-year fixed-rate mortgages for conforming loans of $806,500 or less in the US fell to 6.21%
mortgage applications declined 8.9%, extending an 8.5% drop in the previous week, with the winter storm taking a toll.
